<html>

<title>Ed Facts</title>

<body background="/townhall/FRC/images/bckgnd7.jpg" text="#ff0000" 
vlink="#000000">

<center><h1>ED FACTS - JANUARY 24</h1>
<img src="/townhall/FRC/edfacts/pencil.gif">
</center>
<p>

<font size=+1>

<center><h3>EBONICS DEBATE MOVES TO CAPITOL HILL</h3></center>

<p>

A U.S. Senate committee heard testimony on
Ebonics Thursday.  Sen. Arlen Specter (R-Pa.), Chairman of the
Senate Appropriations Subcommittee on Labor, HHS and Education,
called the hearing to discuss Ebonics in light of federal education
spending.  Current federal policy recognizes Ebonics as a dialect
rather than a language, and therefore excludes it from federal
bilingual education funding.

<p>

Ebonics commentary has appeared on the editorial
pages of papers from Oakland to New York ever since the Oakland
school board passed its infamous resolution on &quot;Black English&quot;
late last month.  The resolution recognized Ebonics as a unique
language -- as opposed to slang or a dialect -- and directed the
school district to begin instructing students in their &quot;primary
language&quot; in addition to standard English.  As a result of
the national outcry, the Oakland school board last week amended
its resolution, removing the reference to Ebonics as black students'
primary language and clarifying that Ebonics would be taught as
a stepping stone to standard English.

<p>

Oakland School District Superintendent Carolyn
Getridge and other district officials were at Thursday's hearing
to defend their Ebonics decision.  Also present was Dr. Robert
L. Williams, who coined the term Ebonics in 1973.

<p>

Conservative commentator Armstrong Williams
testified at the hearing as well.  &quot;What we are seeing with
the Ebonics issue is really about conflicting values in education,&quot;
he noted,  &quot;and, on a broader level, conflicting philosophies
about social understanding and equality.&quot;

<p>

Williams' comments highlighted the importance
of language in unifying a nation:

<p><blockquote>

&quot;When we talk about teaching standard
English to children, we are talking about investing them with
the standard currency of this country.  We are instilling in them
the means to communicate in the marketplace of ideas as well as
the marketplace of commerce and governance.  We are saying to
them, come into the fold, plant your ideas and your strengths
in this land so that we may all be stronger.&quot;

</blockquote><p>

This national comity is a much worthier goal
than the false self-esteem Ebonics would instill if it were given
greater legitimacy.

<p>

<center><h3>DOUBLE STANDARD ON STANDARDS</h3></center>

<p>

President Bill Clinton made a big plug for
national standards while speaking near Chicago this week.  He
accused opponents of national standards of fearing that their
kids couldn't keep up with these rigorous expectations.  Considering
the federal government's current caliber of standards for education,
Clinton's argument is weak:

<p><ul>

<li>When Ohio determined that its high school
graduates would be required to pass a ninth-grade proficiency
test, the federal government brought a suit against the state
on the basis that such a prerequisite was discriminatory -- because
it was too high.

<p>

<li>President Clinton is advancing &quot;America
Reads,&quot; a $2.75 billion scheme to get kids reading by the
end of third grade with the help of a million &quot;volunteers&quot;
(many of whom will be supplied by the Americorps <I>paid</I> service
program).  But why should we give up our high standard that kids
learn to read by <I>first</I> grade with the help of their <I>teachers</I>?

<p>

<li>The <I>National Standards for United States
History</I> included Madonna and the <I>Simpsons</I>, but left
out George Washington's presidency and the U.S. landing on the
moon.

</ul><p>

Even as he urged support for national standards,
Clinton voiced support for local control of schools.  But national
standards threaten, rather than strengthen, local control.  Clinton
can't have it both ways.

<p>

We all agree that we need high standards for
our children's education. The critical question is, whose standards?

<p>

<center><h3>NO MORE VACANCY</h3></center>

<p>

The House Education and the Workforce Committee
has filled its four Republican vacancies.  The new members are:

<p><ul>

Fred Upton (R-Mich.)<br>
Nathan Deal (R-Ga.)<br>
Van Hilleary (R-Tenn.)<br>
Joe Scarborough (R-Fla.)

</ul>

<p><hr width=50%><p>

<font size=-1>
<i><b>Ed Facts</b> is a weekly facsimile publication of Family
Research Council, 801 G St., N.W., Washington, D.C.
20001. Phone:  202-393-2100; FAX:  202-393-2134; Legislative
Hotline: 202-783-HOME; Order line:  800-225-4008; Internet Site:
http://www.frc.org.  Suggested annual donation for <b>Ed
Facts</b>: $25.</i>
</font><p>
