<html>
<head>
<title>NEWS FROM THE HOUSE DEMOCRATIC LEADER</title>
<center>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<h2>News from the House Democratic Leader</h2>
</center>
Thursday, July 6, 1995
<hr>
<h4>Democratic Leader Richard A. Gephardt H-204, U.S. Capitol</h4><p>
<blockquote><i>Remarks by House Democratic Leader Richard A. 
Gephardt "A Democratic plan For America's Economy: Toward 
A Fairer, Simpler, Tax Code." Center for National Policy, Washington, D.C.</i></blockquote><p>

I thank the Center for National Policy for having me here today, and for providing this important forum on issues that matter to America's working families.<p>
I'm here today to talk about our federal income tax. To talk about the steps we must take to fundamentally overhaul a tax system that has become so riddled with loopholes, so tailored to the lobbyists and special interests, that it works against America's hard-working families, when it should be working for them.<p>
That's why I am presenting a tax plan that closes all the loopholes and makes everybody pay their fair share; that permanently ends the influence of the lobbyists and special interests; that dramatically lowers everybody's tax rates, so that 75 percent of all Americans will pay just ten 
percent of their income in taxes; and that requires a national referendum to raise tax rates.<p>
But I'm really here to talk about much, much more than a policy proposal.<p>
I'm here to continue a debate that has been raging in the 104th Congress with every vote, and every policy proposal, and every public pronouncement by members of both parties:<p>
Do we fight to protect, preserve, and defend America's working families and the middle class -- or do we return to the trickle-down travesty that shattered our standard of living, widened the gap between working people and the wealthy, and would sacrifice our children and our elderly 
on the altar of needless tax breaks for the privileged few?<p>
In the boom years of the 80's, two-thirds of all new wealth went to the top one percent of America's households. The bottom eighty percent saw their wealth decline. That is the legacy of Republican government Does that bad turn really deserve another?<p>
Several months ago, in a speech to the Economic Policy Institute, I argued that the Republican Party is now attempting to repeal the Progressive Era and the New Deal by stealth.<p>
That the Republican Party is attempting to force us into a global economic steeplechase with no rules, no order, and no standards -- until most Americans are working longer days and earning third-world wages. <p>
I argued that their opposition to a minimum wage increase -- their insistence on a tax cut tailored to top earners -- their crusade to kill meaningful health care reform last year -- are all part of an agenda that rewards the privileged few, and leaves everybody else out in the cold.<p>
I argued that unless we change the way we do business, both at home and abroad -unless we fight for globalization with rules -- globalization that expands our standards throughout the world, rather than dragging them down --And unless we insist that America's businesses value their people as 
much as their profit then we will be stuck in a devastating downward spiral.<p>
Today, I advance the second chapter of a blueprint for the American economy of the future -- in this case, a proposal for a broad-reaching tax reform that is more than the package of perks for the privileged which the Republicans have offered.<p>
The fact is, while we work to lift wages and incomes at home and abroad -- while we defend our middle class from the ravages of third- and fourth-world competition --We must give Americans the power to run their own economic lives. We must take the decisions and disincentives out of the committee rooms of the Capitol, and put that power back into the living rooms of America. The way to do that is to close the loopholes, lower tax rates, and let families spend their money in ways that are right for them.<p>
I believe that the tax reform plan I am presenting today is right on the merits -- regardless of its context. But that context -- a broader Democratic vision of America's economy and society -- a fierce defense of working families and the middle class -- an economy that upholds family wages, and does not tax them into oblivion -- is vitally important for my party and my country.<p>
At its heart, the debate we are now in asks whether Democrats will fight for our defining values, or whether we will simply surrender to resurgent Republicans, or perhaps only seek to amend and ameliorate the worst of their ideas.<p>
In my judgement, the only way for the Democratic Party to thrive in the 1990's -- or maybe even to survive -- is to advance bold, new ideas -- but ones that are consistent with the oldest, truest Democratic value we know -- to serve and strengthen working families and the middle class.<p>
The way for the Democratic Party to thrive in the 1990's is to resist the temptation to split what are really irreconcilable differences.<p>
You see, Democrats cannot win -- and will not deserve to win -- if we all we have to offer is rusted and recycled Republicanism.<p>
We cannot prevail in a mindless competition to cut deeper, to bash government harder, to balance the budget faster.<p>
Of course, balancing the budget is important. Shrinking the size of government is important. But while we repair the damage of the last generation, we must also build a stronger nation for the next generation.<p>
The Republican vision of America's future is one of lower wages and less job security; of more time on the job and less time with your family; of tax breaks for the few and Medicare cuts for the many.<p>
In Republican America -- where lobbyists write the laws, and government handouts go to the powerful special interests -- no tax break is too brazen, no shelter too shameless, for their privileged patrons.<p>
Democrats must challenge this vision head-on. And this is about more than politics. Throughout this century, the Democratic Party has been the party of working families and the middle class -- the party of jobs and opportunity -- the party of rising wages and strong families.<p>
We speak for those who have no idle investments. We speak for those who have no lobbyists to skew the system to their service.<p>
If Democrats surrender those people and those values, we lose more than the next election. We lose our soul as a party.<p>
I am here to offer a Democratic way to radically reform America's tax system. To say that while we reclaim the global and national economies from the trickle-down terrorists, we must make the tax code work for working families, not special interests and lobbyists.<p>
And I will be continuing this dialogue with other speeches in the coming months ~ talking about ways to lift America's falling wages and incomes; talking about ways to reform our political system, and make campaigns shorter and cheaper; and talking about a new Democratic path to health 
care reform. Just because health care became a problem for the politicians last year doesn't mean it stopped being a problem for hard-working families. Democrats have fought for this issue for a generation, and there is no reason to stop now.<p>
In my view, Democrats must not fight this crucial tax debate on Republican ground. We must not embrace Bill Archer's archly regressive consumption tax. We must not surrender to Dick Armey's flat tax, which fields an army of perks for the privileged. And we must not mount a timid defense of a status quo that is riddled with loopholes, and simply doesn't work for working families.
We can have a tax system that is both simple and fair. We can abandon the maddening complexity, the mind-numbing bureaucracy of today's tax system -- without favoring the loophole -- jumpers over the factory workers.<p>
It doesn't take a tax expert to see the injustice of today's system. You only have to go door to door in my town of St. Louis -- to talk to the hard-working, middle class families who are struggling just to make ends meet, to feel their anger and resentment at a system that favors the experts and insiders over average families.<p>
They know, almost intuitively, that if a privileged few are getting huge tax breaks, and the poorest Americans are paying no taxes, then the middle class gets squeezed to make up the difference.<p>
Decades of toying and tinkering at the margins have only made the problem worse. And I've concluded that the only way to fix anything is to replace everything -- to overhaul the entire system, from top to bottom.<p>
Under my plan, three-fourths of all Americans pay ten percent of their income. The rest pay one of four progressive rates -- to be specific, 20 percent, 26 percent, 32 percent, and 34 percent. The mortgage deduction is maintained, but virtually all other exemptions are eliminated.<p>
Mine is the only tax reform plan that is designed entirely for working families and the middle class. No lobbyist -- no special interest -- no corporate contributor will reap special benefits from its passage.<p>
The gimmicks and giveaways that have cluttered our tax code will be eliminated, once and for all. That means that fringe benefits will be taxable -- but because the basic tax rates will be lowered for every single American, and because the standard deduction will be bigger, most 
American's will pay less, not more, in taxes.<p>
Tax forms will be so simple that they can be printed on a small postcard. For most Americans, thanks to an improved system of withholding, they won't have to file returns at all.<p>
So if you're one of the few who use high-powered attorneys to maneuver the maze of our tax system, then you're not going to like my plan.<p>
But if you want a tax plan that lets most Americans to pay a flat ten percent of their income, without filing a return -If you want a tax plan that insists that everyone pay their fair share -
Then the 10% Tax makes sense for you. And l urge you to call a special number -- (202) 226-3881 -- to get more information about the plan, including a computer disk to help you figure out just how much you'll save on your taxes, and how simple it will be.<p>
My plan takes us back to the first principles of the federal income tax -- principles that have been distorted and defeated with every lobbyists' loophole, with every layer of legalese that has crowded our tax code.<p>
Back in 1913, when the states ratified the 16th Amendment to the Constitution, allowing a federal income tax, the basic purpose was simple:<p>
To collect tax dollars fairly, simply, and broadly, to pay for crucial public purposes.<p>
Today, it has become a test of legal brainpower, an accountants' decathlon, a treasure hunt for hidden deductions and buried tax breaks.<p>
Our tax code has become a dense fog of incentives, inducements, and penalties that distort the most basic economic decisions, constrain the free market, and make it hard for Americans to run their own lives.<p>
The Internal Revenue Service has become a symbol of what is wrong with American government. Mind you, I have no interest in bashing government. My aim is to improve it.<p>
My 10% Tax will enable us to cut the IRS, to make it smaller and less expensive. For the vast majority of Americans, who will not have to file any returns, the IRS will be reduced to little more than a mailing address. I also intend to create a citizens' panel, to make sure that tax forms are 
simple and understandable for those who do have to file them.<p>
My plan begins by ending virtually every exemption, loophole, and tax shelter. With the billions of dollars we save, we will slash tax rates across the board for all Americans. With no special gimmicks and giveaways, the lobbyists who have rigged our tax code for decades will permanently 
lose their seats at the table.<p>
As I have said, there is one single deduction that this plan protects -- the deduction of interest on home mortgages. That's because home ownership is such a basic goal for working and middle class families -- it is such an essential part of the American dream -- that we must do everything we 
can to support and encourage it.<p>
Under my plan, a family of four would pay the ten percent rate up to about 60,000 dollars in income. An individual would pay the ten percent rate up to 32,000 dollars.<p>
For the remaining twenty-five percent, there will be four additional tax rates -- all be lower than under today's tax code.<p>
I am including in my plan a provision that Congress may not raise tax rates without a national referendum -- because I want to end the temptation to start raising tax rates by doling out loopholes. That decision should belong to the American people, not to a Congressional committee. 
If this plan becomes law, the American people can stop reading politicians' lips -and start running their own lives.<p>
Unlike some Republican proposals, the 10% Tax treats so-called "unearned income" -money from stock speculation, capital gains, and idle investment -- the same as income that has been earned the old-fashioned way.<p>
I don't think it makes sense to let supply-side speculators pay no taxes at all -- which is exactly what would happen under the leading Republican plans. Do they believe that money earned through idle investment is somehow better than money earned through sweat, toil, and tears? Whether it is manual labor, or the most sophisticated high-tech services, I believe we must value and encourage productive work, not just passive profit.<p>
The 10% Tax will dramatically scale back the 300-billion-dollar industry of tax advisers and preparers, and the 4.5 billion hours Americans spend each year to prepare their taxes.<p>
The income tax shouldn't be a full employment program for accountants and economists. Under my plan, the only jobs created will come from individual investment and initiative -- from people keeping and using more of their own money -- from families freed from today's tax bureaucracy.<p>
Unlike some Republican proposals, the 10% Tax will not increase the deficit. It will raise as much revenue as today's tax system -- but it will raise it more fairly, since everyone will play by the same rules, whether they hail from Main Street or Easy Street.<p>
We will slash corporate welfare by fifty billion dollars, and use that money to cut taxes for small businesses. It's time to take those tax breaks from the corporations that don't need them, and give them to the small businesses that are the real engines of growth in this country.<p>
Some argue that, instead of my simplified 10% Tax, we should merely end the income tax altogether, and switch to a consumption tax -- a national sales tax on all money that is spent. The argument is that this will increase savings, since money that is saved would not be taxed.<p>
This kind of consumption tax is wrong for several more basic reasons. First, it is plainly and profoundly regressive. Families that earn less will pay a much higher proportion of their income in taxes, because they spend much more of what they earn just to survive.<p>
Second, it would require a massive and sudden increase in the sales tax to raise the necessary revenue. Who can even guess the devastating effects on consumers and retailers when sales taxes are doubled or tripled overnight? Whole industries -- productive industries, ones that make 
more than paperwork -- could be thrown into turmoil. We simply can't take that risk.<p>
Third, at a time when the Labor Department has reported the greatest yearly decline in wages since the 1 840's -- when the invention of the electric loom threw millions of weavers out of work -- trying to 
encourage savings through the tax code is simply beside the point. Whenyou're working two or three jobs just to keep a roof over your head and put food on the table, you can't save money no matter what the tax code says.<p>
People won't save more until they have more. That is why we must turn our attention to falling family incomes, and stop trying to control people's behavior from the committee rooms of the Capitol.<p>
Finally, my 10% Tax is unapologetically progressive.<p>
Since Abraham Lincoln adopted the very first income tax during the Civil War, our tax system has followed this simple progressive principle: those who enjoy more of society's benefits should shoulder a little more of its burdens.<p>
This principle is the cornerstone not just of our tax system, but of a decent, civil society.<p>
Those who have prospered and profited from life's lottery have a moral obligation to share their good fortune. It's a principle as old as the Bible itself.<p>
Let's be very clear what we're talking about today. I know that discussions of our tax code can easily devolve into policy trivia and government jargon.<p>
But my proposal is about something more basic -- more fundamental.<p>
It's about the line worker, the farm hand, the office clerk -- people who can't afford a blue-chip lawyer, and just want a system that isn't stacked against them.<p>
It's about a new age of global competition, when we simply can't sustain a tax code that twists and tortures every economic decision, so that people do what's right for their taxes, instead of what's right for their families and our economy.<p>
And it is about a Democratic vision of a high and rising standard of living -- of fairness and freedom, both in our tax system and in our global economy.<p>
We can't reach our full potential if we have a tax system that works for the few, and punishes the many. We can't build up the middle class by taxing it out of existence. And Democrats cannot endorse a Republican agenda that lavishes more on those who have the most, but destroys the very tax base and consumer base on which they depend.<p>
I would like to believe that both Republicans and Democrats can rally behind this plan -- just as Theodore Roosevelt and William Aft joined hands with populists and progressives to support the original income tax at the turn of this century.<p>
But if that bipartisan support does not come, Democrats must not be afraid to fight for what we believe.<p>
For I believe the 10% Tax is a model for the kind of Arnerica Democrats must champion in the 1 990's -An America that can shatter the ice of its own indifference. An America that is unafraid to rethink its most basic assumptions -But an America that does not bargain away the Democratic values that have built this country, by reducing our two-party system to a one-party budget-cutting machine.<p>
The fact is, the hard-working, middle class families of this nation deserve that kind of America.<p>
That is why Democrats must fight for higher wages, for fairer taxes, for political reform, for better health care, and for the fundamental fairness that is the foundation of our Republic.<p>
The American people need this plan. I believe it can bring us closer to an economy that truly works for working people. An economy as strong and open and optimistic as the one we had when I was growing up in the 50's and 60's.<p>
May that be the mission of the Democratic Party in the 1 990's -- and through our hopes and our hard work, may that be the legacy we leave for our children, and our children's children.<p>
CONTACT: Laura Nichols/Dan Sallick<p>
(202) 225-0100<p>
10% TAX<p>
The 10% Tax would radically reform today's income tax system to enable the vast majority (75%) of all taxpayers to pay their federal income taxes at no more than a 10% rate.<p>
The proposal eliminates virtually every deduction, credit, exclusion and adjustment, to lower tax rates for everyone. The only deduction allowed is for mortgage interest.<p>
A majority of taxpayers would not have to file an income tax return with the federal government. Tax forms would be printed on a small postcard.<p>
To achieve reduction in tax rates, the current tax base would be dramatically broadened. The proposal would retain the current progressivity of the tax code and would not increase the deficit. A family of four, for example, would pay taxes at a 10% rate up to $59,550 and would have $19,350 of their income exempt from federal income taxes altogether.<p>
These changes would make the tax system fairer and simpler and would help to reduce the more than $300 billion and 4.5 billion hours per year that is spent on tax filing and preparation. Average taxpayers will know that everyone else is paying their fair share: high-priced lawyers and accountants won't help the privileged reduce their tax bill.<p>
Unlike a consumption tax, the 10% Tax treats all income the same. Whether a taxpayer earns money from hard work or from investment, the tax treatment will be the same.<p>
75% of all taxpayers pay taxes at no more than a 10% rate and tax rates are lower for all Americans<p>
The 10% Tax closes all loopholes<p>
A majority of taxpayers do not have to file a tax form<p>
A family of four pays no more than 10% up to roughly $60,000 in income<p>
A single individual pays no more than 10% up to roughly $32,000 in income<p>
The deduction for mortgage interest is retained<p>
Tax rates could only change in the future by national referendum<p>
The 10% Tax taxes all income -- earned and unearned -- the same<p>
The 10% Tax does not increase the deficit<p>
The 10% Tax is as progressive as today's tax system<p>
The 10% Tax takes away the lobbyist's seat at the table<p>
The 10% Tax drastically reduces the more than $300 billion and 4.5 billion hours spent on preparing and filing tax returns<p>
The 10% Tax cuts corporate welfare by more than $50 billion and uses that money to cut taxes for small businesses<p>
The 10% Tax ends the distorting effect of the tax code on economic decisions<p>
The 10% Tax promotes more productive investment and jobs<p>
The 10% Tax helps us compete and win in world markets<p>
The 10% Tax allows dramatic cuts in the Internal Revenue Service<p>

